<div class=3D"toc-macro rbtoc1776070300557">
<ul class=3D"toc-indentation">
<li><a href=3D"#OAuth2.0SecurityPatterns=E2=80=94FromCoarse-GrainedAuthoriz=
ationtotoFine-GrainedAuthorization-TableofContents">Table of Contents</a></=
li>
</ul>
</div>
<h2 local-id=3D"52c809ed8c60" id=3D"OAuth2.0SecurityPatterns=E2=80=94FromCo=
arse-GrainedAuthorizationtotoFine-GrainedAuthorization-Context{#context}">C=
ontext {#context}</h2>
<p local-id=3D"32ac3fa38fb3">Modern banking applications delegate authoriza=
tion decisions to a dedicated <strong>Authorization Server (AS)</strong> us=
ing the OAuth 2.0 framework (RFC 6749). In a typical Open Banking or PSD2-c=
ompliant architecture, a client application =E2=80=94 whether a Single Page=
 Application, a mobile app, or a third-party Payment Service Provider =E2=
=80=94 must obtain an access token from the AS before calling protected bac=
kend APIs to initiate wire transfers, read account data, or approve transac=
tions.</p>
<p local-id=3D"d90f965c6c64">OAuth 2.0 was originally designed for broad, c=
oarse-grained delegation scenarios =E2=80=94 for instance, granting a third=
-party application read access to a user's calendar or cloud storage. It wa=
s not designed for the level of precision required by financial transaction=
s, where authorization must be bound to a specific amount, a specific benef=
iciary account, and a specific debtor account, all at the moment of user co=
nsent.</p>
<p local-id=3D"b890276c999f">Two key extensions to OAuth 2.0 address these =
gaps:</p>
<ul local-id=3D"6cf0b3f6-146a-4871-8ca9-470e5766b2d6">
<li local-id=3D"b5fbf2e9-c34b-47bf-b84f-c02ac3c09237">
<p local-id=3D"98fddf805cf9"><strong>RFC 9396 =E2=80=94 Rich Authorization =
Requests (RAR):</strong> enables clients to describe precisely what they wa=
nt to do, using a structured <code>authorization_details</code> object inst=
ead of a simple scope string. The AS can then enforce fine-grained policies=
 and render an informed consent screen.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"a1c3d70c-d75a-442e-b889-23e7839814cc">
<p local-id=3D"f6bc117cd18c"><strong>RFC 9126 =E2=80=94 Pushed Authorizatio=
n Requests (PAR):</strong> enables clients to send the Authorization Reques=
t to the AS via an authenticated back-channel HTTP POST, rather than embedd=
ing all parameters in a browser redirect URL. This keeps sensitive paramete=
rs out of URLs and all systems that log them.</p></li>
</ul>
<p local-id=3D"21a54e076088">These two extensions are complementary. RAR so=
lves the <strong>semantic</strong> problem (what is being authorized). PAR =
solves the <strong>transport</strong> problem (how the authorization reques=
t is transmitted securely). In a banking context, both are required togethe=
r.</p>
<hr local-id=3D"f416d62e-b15c-48d5-837d-3df882ee1872">
<h2 local-id=3D"80474c29532f" id=3D"OAuth2.0SecurityPatterns=E2=80=94FromCo=
arse-GrainedAuthorizationtotoFine-GrainedAuthorization-Part1=E2=80=94Classi=
cOAuth2.0vsRichAuthorizationRequests(RAR){#part-1}">Part 1 =E2=80=94 Classi=
c OAuth 2.0 vs Rich Authorization Requests (RAR) {#part-1}</h2>
<h3 local-id=3D"c6a895633922" id=3D"OAuth2.0SecurityPatterns=E2=80=94FromCo=
arse-GrainedAuthorizationtotoFine-GrainedAuthorization-1.1TheProblemwithCla=
ssicOAuth2.0Scopes">1.1 The Problem with Classic OAuth 2.0 Scopes</h3>
<p local-id=3D"680ce41e7afd">In classic OAuth 2.0, the authorization reques=
t carries a <code>scope</code> parameter =E2=80=94 a space-separated list o=
f string tokens that define what access is being requested. For a banking a=
pplication initiating a wire transfer, a typical scope looks like:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">scope=
=3Dopenid wire_transfer accounts:read</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p local-id=3D"0da3992c2a19">This approach has fundamental limitations in a=
 financial context:</p>
<ul local-id=3D"f8a9b282-85e0-47f4-94c8-cfaceb115f79">
<li local-id=3D"2d6e602f-279d-41db-b391-a7f3b3fcea7c">
<p local-id=3D"347f10937f0d"><strong>No transaction binding.</strong> The s=
cope <code>wire_transfer</code> grants blanket permission to initiate any w=
ire transfer, for any amount, to any beneficiary. There is no mechanism in =
the standard scope system to restrict a token to a specific transaction. A =
token issued in this flow is, by construction, reusable for any transfer th=
e resource server permits for that user.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"1fd3363c-6aeb-4aeb-8662-d0bd23d6e4b3">
<p local-id=3D"9b2554a748e4"><strong>Uninformed user consent.</strong> The =
consent screen displayed by the AS can only show a generic label such as "W=
ire Transfer Access". The end user cannot see that they are authorizing a t=
ransfer of EUR 47,500.00 to a specific IBAN. This is in direct conflict wit=
h PSD2 RTS Article 4, which requires explicit, transaction-specific consent=
 for payment initiation.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"e9a412a6-e1ce-4b5e-a65d-01214cc8859a">
<p local-id=3D"92926529cf79"><strong>No AS-level business rule enforcement.=
</strong> Because the AS does not know the amount, the destination account,=
 or the source account at authorization time, it cannot enforce rules such =
as daily transfer limits, beneficiary whitelists or blacklists, dual-approv=
al thresholds for high-value transactions, or currency restrictions. All va=
lidation is deferred to the backend resource server =E2=80=94 after the tok=
en has already been issued.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"e1b45939-81cd-484e-be41-4dd7094f000f">
<p local-id=3D"c0b41e70edf9"><strong>Token reuse and replay risk.</strong> =
A token issued for <code>scope=3Dwire_transfer</code> can be presented by a=
n attacker (or a compromised client) to initiate a different transaction th=
an the one the user consented to. The token carries no cryptographic bindin=
g to the original transaction intent.</p></li>
</ul>
<p local-id=3D"4fbe28fdd336"><strong>Sequence diagram =E2=80=94 Classic OAu=
th 2.0 (Authorization Code + PKCE)</strong></p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">[REPLAC=
E WITH MERMAID IMAGE]

sequenceDiagram
    participant U   as User
    participant App as Client Application
    participant AS  as Authorization Server
    participant RS  as Resource Server (API)

    U-&gt;&gt;App: Initiate wire transfer (amount, IBAN, beneficiary)
    App-&gt;&gt;AS: GET /authorize?scope=3Dopenid+wire_transfer&amp;respons=
e_type=3Dcode&amp;...
    Note over AS: Receives only a scope string =E2=80=94 no transaction det=
ail
    AS--&gt;&gt;U: Login + consent screen ("Wire Transfer Access")
    U-&gt;&gt;AS: Authenticate and approve
    AS--&gt;&gt;App: 302 redirect =E2=80=94 ?code=3DAUTH_CODE
    App-&gt;&gt;AS: POST /token (code + code_verifier)
    AS--&gt;&gt;App: access_token { scope: "wire_transfer" }
    App-&gt;&gt;RS: POST /transfers (Bearer token + transaction data in bod=
y)
    Note over RS: Validates token scope only =E2=80=94 no AS-level binding =
to transaction
    RS--&gt;&gt;App: 200 Transfer initiated</pre>
</div>
</div>
<blockquote local-id=3D"0e650c89-0cf3-4574-9541-c7c622eb0680">
<p local-id=3D"3c970448aadf">=E2=9A=A0=EF=B8=8F <strong>Key issue:</strong>=
 The AS has no knowledge of the specific transaction being authorized. The =
issued token is reusable for any transfer. Consent is generic and does not =
satisfy transaction-level regulatory requirements.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr local-id=3D"3be21ce6-7abf-4c7e-bd89-ff7b79d692b2">
<h3 local-id=3D"67903ead542c" id=3D"OAuth2.0SecurityPatterns=E2=80=94FromCo=
arse-GrainedAuthorizationtotoFine-GrainedAuthorization-1.2TheSolution=E2=80=
=94RichAuthorizationRequests(RFC9396)">1.2 The Solution =E2=80=94 Rich Auth=
orization Requests (RFC 9396)</h3>
<p local-id=3D"1b8101698b74">RAR introduces the <code>authorization_details=
</code> request parameter, which carries a structured JSON array describing=
 exactly what the client is requesting authorization for. Instead of a vagu=
e scope string, the AS receives a precise, machine-readable description of =
the intended operation, typed according to a domain-specific schema.</p>
<p local-id=3D"e2ec65ecd836">For a wire transfer use case, the <code>author=
ization_details</code> object would be structured as follows:</p>
<p local-id=3D"20168ff1a7eb">json</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">authori=
zation_details=3D[
  {
    "type": "wire_transfer",
    "instructedAmount": {
      "currency": "EUR",
      "amount": "47500.00"
    },
    "creditorAccount": {
      "iban": "FR7630006000011234567890189"
    },
    "creditorName": "ACME Corp SAS",
    "debtorAccount": {
      "iban": "FR7630004000031234567890143"
    },
    "remittanceInformation": "Invoice 2024-089"
  }
]</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p local-id=3D"88dd4132f1ea">The <code>type</code> field is a string that i=
dentifies the authorization schema. The AS uses it to select the appropriat=
e policy engine and consent template. All other fields are schema-specific =
and defined by the authorization domain (e.g., Open Banking, Berlin Group N=
extGenPSD2).</p>
<p local-id=3D"b5311abb4fbf"><strong>What RAR enables at the AS level:</str=
ong></p>
<ul local-id=3D"c7411115-dba4-451d-98d7-b9aefe56ce39">
<li local-id=3D"60bc9aae-aba8-4582-b1a1-b79d8367d1ba">
<p local-id=3D"17d7b1c08c29"><strong>Informed user consent.</strong> The AS=
 renders a consent screen showing the exact transaction details: "You are a=
bout to authorize a wire transfer of EUR 47,500.00 to ACME Corp SAS (FR7630=
006000011234567890189). Confirm?" The user signs off on the exact operation=
, not a generic permission class.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"40caa456-7d5e-46ef-b717-4c8cc36745bf">
<p local-id=3D"d9b372e3f78a"><strong>AS-level business rule enforcement.</s=
trong> The AS can validate the <code>instructedAmount</code> against the us=
er's configured daily limit, verify that the <code>debtorAccount</code> IBA=
N belongs to the authenticated user, check the <code>creditorAccount</code>=
 against a fraud watchlist, and enforce dual-approval workflows for high-va=
lue transactions =E2=80=94 all before issuing any token.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"9ba1e9c7-cf83-4e12-837b-ce4efcabc3f0">
<p local-id=3D"7141086f572e"><strong>Token binding to transaction intent.</=
strong> The AS embeds the <code>authorization_details</code> object into th=
e issued access token as a claim. The resource server verifies that the tok=
en presented matches the transaction parameters in the request body. A stol=
en token cannot be replayed for a different amount or a different IBAN.</p>=
</li>
<li local-id=3D"f1f93aac-1967-4c71-8ace-baf4cfe7bac8">
<p local-id=3D"4168b30bd196"><strong>Regulatory compliance.</strong> Transa=
ction-specific consent satisfies the PSD2 RTS requirements for Strong Custo=
mer Authentication (SCA) and provides a traceable, non-repudiable consent r=
ecord tied to the exact transaction parameters.</p></li>
</ul>
<p local-id=3D"8b8d7c147cd5"><strong>Sequence diagram =E2=80=94 OAuth 2.0 +=
 RAR</strong></p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">[REPLAC=
E WITH MERMAID IMAGE]

sequenceDiagram
    participant U   as User
    participant App as Client Application
    participant AS  as Authorization Server
    participant RS  as Resource Server (API)

    U-&gt;&gt;App: Initiate wire transfer (amount, IBAN, beneficiary)
    App-&gt;&gt;App: Build authorization_details JSON object
    App-&gt;&gt;AS: GET /authorize?authorization_details=3D[{type:wire_tran=
sfer, amount:47500, creditorIBAN:FR76...}]&amp;...
    Note over AS: Parses authorization_details, selects policy and consent =
template
    AS--&gt;&gt;U: Consent: "Authorize EUR 47,500.00 to ACME Corp SAS (FR76=
...)?"
    U-&gt;&gt;AS: Authenticate and confirm
    AS--&gt;&gt;App: 302 redirect =E2=80=94 ?code=3DAUTH_CODE
    App-&gt;&gt;AS: POST /token
    AS--&gt;&gt;App: access_token { authorization_details: [{type:wire_tran=
sfer, amount:47500, ...}] }
    App-&gt;&gt;RS: POST /transfers (Bearer token)
    RS-&gt;&gt;RS: Verify token.authorization_details matches request body
    RS--&gt;&gt;App: 200 Transfer initiated</pre>
</div>
</div>
<hr local-id=3D"5c7218fb-845c-4206-a33d-073c862c3c8d">
