<hr local-id=3D"e61de0ac-303d-4ff4-9c19-cd2847fb9bff">
<h2 local-id=3D"bf6da6253906" id=3D"OAuth2.0SecurityPatterns=E2=80=94FromCo=
arse-GrainedAuthorizationtotoFine-GrainedAuthorization-Part2=E2=80=94OAuth2=
.0+RARwithoutPAR{#part-2}">Part 2 =E2=80=94 OAuth 2.0 + RAR without PAR {#p=
art-2}</h2>
<h3 local-id=3D"2e3c70778ca2" id=3D"OAuth2.0SecurityPatterns=E2=80=94FromCo=
arse-GrainedAuthorizationtotoFine-GrainedAuthorization-2.1TheProblem=E2=80=
=94RARSolvesSemanticsbutNotTransport">2.1 The Problem =E2=80=94 RAR Solves =
Semantics but Not Transport</h3>
<p local-id=3D"9242764b13ef">RAR resolves the authorization granularity pro=
blem. The AS now knows exactly what it is authorizing. However, RFC 9396 do=
es not mandate or define any specific transport mechanism for the Authoriza=
tion Request. Without PAR, the default transport remains a browser GET redi=
rect, which means the <code>authorization_details</code> JSON object is URL=
-encoded and appended as a query parameter to the Authorization Request URL=
.</p>
<p local-id=3D"dad82d6861c4">This creates a critical security exposure: the=
 most sensitive data in the entire transaction =E2=80=94 the transfer amoun=
t, the beneficiary IBAN, the debtor account identifier, and the remittance =
reference =E2=80=94 is transmitted in cleartext as part of a URL. That URL =
passes through every system between the user's browser and the Authorizatio=
n Server.</p>
<p local-id=3D"1dac42eb82e8"><strong>Concrete example =E2=80=94 Authorizati=
on Request URL with RAR, without PAR:</strong></p>
<p local-id=3D"cbd0a5b2f01a">The following is an example of an Authorizatio=
n Request URL as it would appear in the browser address bar and in any HTTP=
 log:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">GET /re=
alms/banking-poc/protocol/openid-connect/auth
  ?response_type=3Dcode
  &amp;client_id=3Dwire-transfer-spa
  &amp;redirect_uri=3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Flocalhost%3A8000%2Findex.html
  &amp;scope=3Dopenid+wire_transfer
  &amp;state=3D57f5a653-ef18-474d-8541-87b6cf0fe817
  &amp;code_challenge=3Ds8e5ePqzS7bwGPKPgRwp0m8iflXemf8Ryn9RJrvMiOI
  &amp;code_challenge_method=3DS256
  &amp;authorization_details=3D%5B%7B%22type%22%3A%22wire_transfer%22%2C
    %22instructedAmount%22%3A%7B%22currency%22%3A%22EUR%22%2C
    %22amount%22%3A%2247500.00%22%7D%2C           =E2=86=90 AMOUNT IN CLEAR=
TEXT
    %22creditorAccount%22%3A%7B
    %22iban%22%3A%22FR7630006000011234567890189%22%7D%2C  =E2=86=90 BENEFIC=
IARY IBAN
    %22creditorName%22%3A%22ACME+Corp+SAS%22%2C          =E2=86=90 BENEFICI=
ARY NAME
    %22debtorAccount%22%3A%7B
    %22iban%22%3A%22FR7630004000031234567890143%22%7D%2C  =E2=86=90 DEBTOR =
IBAN
    %22remittanceInformation%22%3A%22Invoice+2024-089%22
  %7D%5D</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p local-id=3D"6059306241d0">Once decoded (percent-decoding is trivial and =
automatic in any HTTP tool or log viewer), the <code>authorization_details<=
/code> value is:</p>
<p local-id=3D"aad26469b3af">json</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">[{
  "type": "wire_transfer",
  "instructedAmount": { "currency": "EUR", "amount": "47500.00" },
  "creditorAccount": { "iban": "FR7630006000011234567890189" },
  "creditorName": "ACME Corp SAS",
  "debtorAccount": { "iban": "FR7630004000031234567890143" },
  "remittanceInformation": "Invoice 2024-089"
}]</pre>
</div>
</div>
<blockquote local-id=3D"265a2fe9-0c54-463f-8f8b-9c72ef11e070">
<p local-id=3D"9bcd84904ac0">=E2=9A=A0=EF=B8=8F <strong>Important:</strong>=
 Percent-encoding is a transport encoding for URL-unsafe characters. It is =
not encryption and provides no confidentiality. Any system that records the=
 URL records the complete, immediately decodable financial transaction data=
.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr local-id=3D"1a82e605-05b6-48e3-9161-26f8407badae">
<h3 local-id=3D"7b332ea1aeef" id=3D"OAuth2.0SecurityPatterns=E2=80=94FromCo=
arse-GrainedAuthorizationtotoFine-GrainedAuthorization-2.2AttackSurface=E2=
=80=94WheretheDataLeaks">2.2 Attack Surface =E2=80=94 Where the Data Leaks<=
/h3>
<p local-id=3D"4150af8ddec6">The following exposure vectors are present in =
any standard enterprise or cloud environment when RAR is used without PAR:<=
/p>
<ul local-id=3D"36e63747-6c26-4a2f-a5b3-e0f2c974f0cf">
<li local-id=3D"dd568e13-ec02-44d9-b8be-49ff5afa1530">
<p local-id=3D"1da6590cb71b"><strong>Browser navigation history.</strong> A=
ll major browsers persist the full URL =E2=80=94 including all query parame=
ters =E2=80=94 in the user's navigation history. Any person or software wit=
h access to the browser profile (other users on a shared machine, malware, =
browser sync services) can read the IBAN and transfer amount from history e=
ntries.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"a7f0c6e2-bcfa-49a1-ab6d-43b7e5b7611c">
<p local-id=3D"80a2e122ce80"><strong>Corporate TLS-inspecting proxy.</stron=
g> Enterprise proxy solutions perform SSL/TLS interception and log the full=
 URL of every HTTPS request. The <code>authorization_details</code> payload=
 is stored in proxy access logs, typically retained for months and accessib=
le to network operations teams without specific authorization controls.</p>=
</li>
<li local-id=3D"5cadf6a6-ca64-43a4-bc82-d725f06b71fe">
<p local-id=3D"be577bfff18b"><strong>Authorization Server access logs.</str=
ong> Most AS implementations =E2=80=94 including Keycloak, PingFederate, an=
d ForgeRock AM =E2=80=94 log incoming requests to the <code>/authorize</cod=
e> endpoint, including all query parameters, at INFO or DEBUG level by defa=
ult. Every wire transfer attempted through the system creates a log entry c=
ontaining the full financial details.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"87f1bccf-689a-4b8b-9154-1c1ed2cb2f7a">
<p local-id=3D"22027b6bd04d"><strong>HTTP Referer header leakage.</strong> =
If the AS page loads any external resource =E2=80=94 analytics scripts, web=
 fonts, CDN-hosted assets, or error tracking SDKs =E2=80=94 the browser inc=
ludes the current page URL in the <code>Referer</code> (or <code>Referrer-P=
olicy</code>-controlled) header of those sub-requests. Transaction data may=
 be transmitted to third-party servers outside the institution's control.</=
p></li>
<li local-id=3D"1df3ca6e-4d1f-4e26-9270-5ae9341836bc">
<p local-id=3D"32800c88f735"><strong>SIEM and network monitoring infrastruc=
ture.</strong> DNS logs, NetFlow records, and HTTP access logs collected by=
 SIEM platforms record request URLs. In regulated environments, this data i=
s retained for years, creating a long-lived, queryable record of financial =
transaction details that may be accessible to a wider audience than intende=
d.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"58582273-03f6-48e0-b50c-1f7b31252361">
<p local-id=3D"70e47d567997"><strong>Browser extensions.</strong> Extension=
s with the <code>tabs</code> or <code>webNavigation</code> permissions can =
read and exfiltrate query parameters from any URL the user visits, includin=
g Authorization Request URLs. Malicious or compromised extensions represent=
 a realistic exfiltration vector for this data.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"be4e424e-d833-47ba-b0d8-389e11affca5">
<p local-id=3D"80df27d0a4ee"><strong>Shared screen and shoulder surfing.</s=
trong> In environments where users share screens during support calls, scre=
en recordings, or remote assistance sessions, a browser address bar display=
ing a transfer amount and full IBAN constitutes a direct, observable inform=
ation disclosure.</p></li>
</ul>
<p local-id=3D"32dbacfffb23"><strong>Sequence diagram =E2=80=94 RAR without=
 PAR: exposure points</strong></p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">[REPLAC=
E WITH MERMAID IMAGE]

sequenceDiagram
    participant U   as User Browser
    participant P   as Corporate Proxy (TLS inspection)
    participant AS  as Authorization Server
    participant L3  as Third-party resource (font, analytics)

    Note over U,AS: All authorization_details travel in the URL =E2=80=94 v=
isible at every hop

    U-&gt;&gt;P: GET /authorize?authorization_details=3D[amount=3D47500, IB=
AN=3DFR76...]
    Note over P: =E2=9A=A0 LOGGED =E2=80=94 full URL including IBAN and amo=
unt stored in proxy logs
    P-&gt;&gt;AS: Forwarded GET with full URL
    Note over AS: =E2=9A=A0 LOGGED =E2=80=94 /authorize request recorded in=
 AS access logs
    AS--&gt;&gt;U: Login page served (URL already persisted in browser hist=
ory)
    Note over U: =E2=9A=A0 Browser history =E2=80=94 URL with IBAN and amou=
nt persisted locally
    AS-&gt;&gt;L3: Load external resource (font, analytics)
    Note over L3: =E2=9A=A0 Referer header may carry Authorization Request =
URL
    U-&gt;&gt;AS: POST credentials
    AS--&gt;&gt;U: 302 redirect to callback?code=3DAUTH_CODE</pre>
</div>
</div>
<hr local-id=3D"581e2e13-7eab-4f1c-a124-f86f4c300a12">
<h3 local-id=3D"ebfe2eccd68d" id=3D"OAuth2.0SecurityPatterns=E2=80=94FromCo=
arse-GrainedAuthorizationtotoFine-GrainedAuthorization-2.3TheSolution=E2=80=
=94PushedAuthorizationRequests(RFC9126)">2.3 The Solution =E2=80=94 Pushed =
Authorization Requests (RFC 9126)</h3>
<p local-id=3D"11c02e51b0ab">PAR fundamentally changes the transport mechan=
ism of the Authorization Request. Instead of embedding all parameters in a =
browser GET redirect URL, the client first sends the full Authorization Req=
uest to a dedicated <code>/par</code> endpoint at the AS via an authenticat=
ed HTTPS POST. The parameters travel in the body of that POST request =E2=
=80=94 never in a URL.</p>
<p local-id=3D"49b9689297f6">The AS validates the request, stores it server=
-side, and returns a short-lived, opaque <code>request_uri</code>. The clie=
nt then initiates the browser redirect using only the <code>client_id</code=
> and this <code>request_uri</code>. The URL visible in the browser contain=
s no sensitive data.</p>
<p local-id=3D"618e82ee4c2e"><strong>PAR flow =E2=80=94 concrete HTTP excha=
nge:</strong></p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">// Step=
 1 =E2=80=94 Client sends full Authorization Request via back-channel POST
// Parameters are in the HTTPS request body =E2=80=94 never in a URL

POST /realms/banking-poc/protocol/openid-connect/ext/par/request
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded
Authorization: Basic &lt;client_credentials&gt;

response_type=3Dcode
&amp;client_id=3Dwire-transfer-spa
&amp;redirect_uri=3Dhttps://app.example.com/callback
&amp;scope=3Dopenid+wire_transfer
&amp;code_challenge=3Ds8e5ePqzS7bwGPKPgRwp0m8iflXemf8Ryn9RJrvMiOI
&amp;code_challenge_method=3DS256
&amp;authorization_details=3D[{
  "type":"wire_transfer",
  "instructedAmount":{"currency":"EUR","amount":"47500.00"},
  "creditorAccount":{"iban":"FR7630006000011234567890189"},
  "creditorName":"ACME Corp SAS",
  "debtorAccount":{"iban":"FR7630004000031234567890143"}
}]


// Step 2 =E2=80=94 AS responds with an opaque request_uri (valid ~60 secon=
ds)

HTTP/1.1 201 Created
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "request_uri": "urn:ietf:params:oauth:request_uri:6esc_11ACC5bwc014ltc14e=
Y22c",
  "expires_in": 60
}


// Step 3 =E2=80=94 Browser redirect contains NO sensitive data

GET /realms/banking-poc/protocol/openid-connect/auth
  ?client_id=3Dwire-transfer-spa
  &amp;request_uri=3Durn:ietf:params:oauth:request_uri:6esc_11ACC5bwc014ltc=
14eY22c</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p local-id=3D"f87f54f7dfa2">The browser address bar =E2=80=94 and every pr=
oxy, log, SIEM, and monitoring system =E2=80=94 only ever sees the opaque <=
code>request_uri</code>. The financial details are stored server-side at th=
e AS, transmitted only over the already-authenticated, server-to-server HTT=
PS back-channel.</p>
<p local-id=3D"d72b69e781f7"><strong>Sequence diagram =E2=80=94 OAuth 2.0 +=
 RAR + PAR (complete secure flow)</strong></p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">[REPLAC=
E WITH MERMAID IMAGE]

sequenceDiagram
    participant U   as User Browser
    participant App as Client Application
    participant AS  as Authorization Server (/par + /authorize)
    participant RS  as Resource Server (API)

    U-&gt;&gt;App: Initiate wire transfer (amount, IBAN, beneficiary)
    App-&gt;&gt;App: Build authorization_details object

    App-&gt;&gt;AS: POST /par (body: authorization_details + PKCE params + =
scopes)
    Note over AS: Validates client credentials, stores request server-side =
securely
    AS--&gt;&gt;App: { request_uri: "urn:ietf:...xyz", expires_in: 60 }

    App-&gt;&gt;U: Redirect to /authorize?client_id=3D...&amp;request_uri=
=3Durn:ietf:...xyz
    Note over U: =E2=9C=94 URL contains no sensitive data =E2=80=94 safe in=
 history, logs, proxies

    AS--&gt;&gt;U: Consent: "Authorize EUR 47,500.00 to ACME Corp SAS (FR76=
...)?"
    U-&gt;&gt;AS: Authenticate and confirm
    AS--&gt;&gt;U: 302 redirect =E2=80=94 callback?code=3DAUTH_CODE

    App-&gt;&gt;AS: POST /token (code + code_verifier)
    AS--&gt;&gt;App: access_token { authorization_details: [{...}] }

    App-&gt;&gt;RS: POST /transfers (Bearer token)
    RS-&gt;&gt;RS: Verify token.authorization_details matches request body
    RS--&gt;&gt;App: 200 Transfer initiated</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p local-id=3D"c51c8a8441e5">PAR also provides an important secondary benef=
it: the AS can validate and reject a malformed or policy-violating Authoriz=
ation Request at the <code>/par</code> step, before any browser redirect oc=
curs. The user never sees an error page mid-flow, and the client receives a=
 structured error response it can handle programmatically.</p>
<hr local-id=3D"3d1d793b-a3f7-48d2-bd70-6d6ee95913b7">
<h3 local-id=3D"8ab5a3e676b4" id=3D"OAuth2.0SecurityPatterns=E2=80=94FromCo=
arse-GrainedAuthorizationtotoFine-GrainedAuthorization-2.4WhyRARandPARMustB=
eUsedTogether">2.4 Why RAR and PAR Must Be Used Together</h3>
<p local-id=3D"46718b806f78">RAR and PAR address complementary and orthogon=
al problems. Neither extension is sufficient alone in a financial services =
context.</p>
